                                youtubeUrl="https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/VHoPJDrt8kE"/>
                            <container
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545825687,1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545835982,1653545835879]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2023-01-24T15:53:38.739-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-01-24T15:53:38.739-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <title2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545824678,1651545825694]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-05-08T09:50:02.091-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Removing barriers for students"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-01-24T15:42:26.666-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>Bailey, who went on to earn a master’s degree in education and self-publish two books, was recently named the first-ever recipient of the Communities In Schools Bill and Jean Milliken Fellowship. As a policy fellow, Bailey is responsible for finding ways to advance the work of CIS on a national level and give voice to the next generation of leaders and thinkers.&lt;br>&#xa;&amp;nbsp;&lt;br>&#xa;With a focus on removing barriers for students at risk of dropping out, CIS will soon be able to serve about 70,000 additional students in more schools across the United States after&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href=&quot;https://news.abbvie.com/news/press-releases/abbvie-donates-55-million-to-three-education-nonprofits-supporting-underserved-youth-in-chicago-across-america.htm&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; title=&quot; receiving a $30 million donation from AbbVie. &quot;>receiving a $30 million donation from AbbVie.&lt;/a>&amp;nbsp;This is the largest donation in Communities In Schools’ 40-year history.&lt;br>&#xa;&amp;nbsp;&lt;br>&#xa;The CIS model centers resources on the students with the highest need, making strong connections with them through school-based coordinators. CIS’ ability to make a deep impact for students aligns with AbbVie’s long-standing commitment to education partners that help overcome the academic achievement gap for children in underserved areas.&lt;/p>&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                                <separator
                                    cq:styleIds="[1662756423318]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2023-02-02T10:26:05.225-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-02-02T10:26:05.225-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/separator/v2/separator"/>
                                <title
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545825694]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2023-01-24T15:42:36.716-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-05-08T09:50:12.049-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Seeing more clearly"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2023-01-24T15:43:38.595-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-01-24T15:44:04.270-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>Bailey first learned of CIS during seventh grade, when a teacher noticed he couldn’t see the lesson on the board. She referred him to the nonprofit, and soon after Bailey got his first pair of glasses. His site coordinator, who continued to serve as a caring adult for Bailey well beyond middle school, helped him get medical insurance, dental work, mentoring and counseling.&lt;br>&#xa;&lt;br>&#xa;Bailey enrolled in every CIS program available, including after-school activities and summer programs that often provided his only meals, along with transportation home. Bailey grew close to the bus driver and his wife and sons, spending time at their home.&lt;/p>&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                                <text_413138798
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2023-01-24T16:23:08.229-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-01-24T16:23:26.806-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="schafsm"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>On a summer evening, after being dropped off at a home with no lights and no parents, Fredrick called the driver – Mr. Cofield – and asked to stay over at his house. A single night with the Cofields turned into six years, marked with family dinners, time together at church and lots of studying.&lt;br>&#xa;&amp;nbsp;&lt;br>&#xa;With support from the Cofields and his CIS coordinator, Bailey began to see a different future for himself. His grades improved, as did his behavior at school.&amp;nbsp;&lt;br>&#xa;&amp;nbsp;&lt;br>&#xa;“Communities In Schools means that you don’t just have to settle in your current situation,” Bailey says. “Because there was a moment in my life where I wanted to settle and say to myself, this is life, and I will be just like my mom, just like my dad.”&lt;/p>&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container>
                        </par_12>
